Introduction¶

There are two unique datasets included for chronic kidney disease (CKD)- a gene dataset and a risk factor dataset, both are collected from patients. The gene and risk factor data is not collected from the same group as that data was not avaliable, however overall we are looking at various factors that contribute to CKD. We decided to focus on CKD as we originally had many datasets from many disease and it was a lot more data so we shifted to CKD, but we may consider using the additional data in the Machine learning part if we can make a relevant model, and doing further statistical analysis on that if needed.

gene_df= gene_df.rename(columns={'13-C':'13-E','14-C':'14-E','15-C':'15-E','16-C':'16-E','17-C':'17-E','18-C':'18-E','19-C':'19-E','20-C':'20-E','21-C':'21-E'})

print(gene_df.info())

#While the rest of the data is important, for our purpose, we only want to look at the most up/downregulated genes to associate the disease with
#This is a huge set, so we will find our focus and clean the data after we identify about 50 candidates for up, and 50 down

#Wanting to choose the most upregulated genes in CKD, we sort the data through the Foldchange value(amount of change between control and experimental)
gene_df.head()

#Choose top 50 upregulated(50 gives enough to find the most upregulated ones, AND significant ones to sort, ofcourse can add more if once you look at it, all are not significant), create new dataframe to work
up=pd.DataFrame
up=gene_df.sort_values("Foldchange",ascending=False)
up=up.head(50)

#sort through the most significant values(adjusted pvalue), many high fold change ones are not as significant and have outliers, so they are not as strong candidates and need to be considered later/cleaned
up=up.sort_values("FDR")
up


#up/down regulated genes have differing biological signifiance
#same as above in upreg, make new dataframe but for downregulated genes
down=pd.DataFrame
down=gene_df.sort_values("Foldchange").head(50)
down=down.sort_values("FDR")
down

#the data in each sample is amount of counts of gene expressed
#looking at the data, there are some clear outliers we can remove(ex. all 0, except one huge value in one sample= no real regulation, ex. huge differences within group, 1000 or 50= no reg)

up=up.drop([up.index[2]])

Part 2: Exploratory Data Analysis for Gene Data¶

1. Pearson Correlation

In understanding if a gene is significantly showing regulation, we want to check there is correlation in samples, and they are actually regulated in a direction. Patient data is variable as humans are naturally going to have genetic varaition, but if all samples in a group(C or E) are correlated, then a defined gene can be possibly making the changes genetically regulated.

We want to understand if these samples are correlated to themselves enough to prove its not just random genetic changes

The heatmap helps visualize the correlation amongst the samples. At the top left, the lighter square of all of the control samples, shows they are more correlated amongst each other than among CKD patients. This helps understand the random variation among the genes in the people is not just random, but the similiarity is related to the genetic disease factor. Same with the ckd patients. The big light square in the bottom right shows the patients samples are correlated better than compared to controls, as those cmoparing the ckd patients and controls are darker. The darker square is closer to 0, so not correlated, and lighter is closer to 1, 1 being correlated, so you can get an idea of the whole dataset and sample group being correlated due to disease.

We beter visualize this to each individual sample in the upregulated genes below. Zooming in on an exmaple of pearson correlation in two controls, two ckd patients, and control vs ckd. You can see the pearson correlation coefficient (r) is close to 1 in the grouped samples, while it is close to 0 in the control vs ckd. A larger pairs plot is formed to get an idea of the entire data and every pair, not just a couple specific ones, showing a trend like the above heatmap

In [4]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from scipy.stats import pearsonr
#control correlation
a=up['22-C']
b=up['23-C']
corr, _ = pearsonr(a, b)
print("r=", corr)
plt.figure()
plt.scatter(a,b)
m, b =np.polyfit(a,b,1)
plt.plot(x, m*x + b)
plt.title("Sample Correlation:Controls")
plt.xlabel("22-C")
plt.ylabel("23-C")

plt.show()


#ckd correlation
d=up['15-E']
c=up['17-E']
corr, _ = pearsonr(d,c)
print("r=", corr)
plt.figure()
plt.scatter(d,c)
m, b=np.polyfit(d,c,1)
plt.plot(d,m*d+b)
plt.title("Sample Correlation:CKD Patients")
plt.xlabel("15-E")
plt.ylabel("17-E")

plt.show()

#control vs ckd
x=up['24-C']
y=up['17-E']
plt.figure()
plt.scatter(x,y)
m, b =np.polyfit(x,y,1)
plt.plot(x, m*x + b)
plt.title("Sample Correlation: Control vs CKD Patients")
plt.xlabel("24-C")
plt.ylabel("17-E")
corr, _ = pearsonr(x, y)
print("r=", corr)
plt.show()

The downregulated genes samples are also more correlated in groups, like the upregulated genes. Seeing more correlation in the controls, and in he ckd patients, then betwen control vs ckd patients.

Hypothesis Testing- Mann Whitney¶

We want to understand whether the differences in the gene expression in groups are large enough to be understood as really upregulated and if the change in expression is relevant enough to consider disease relation to the disease.

We will peform a Mann-Whitney test, we want to compare the means of genes expressed in control and pkd patient samples. We assume the groups are independent of one another. There is so few samples, there is no way to assume normal distribution with only 3 controls-thus Mann- Whitney is ideal. We can use a significance level of .05 for the test.

The genes will be tested separately, so PTIX2 gets its own test, and ALX1 also does. The point is to look at each gene, to test if there is difference in each expression in patients in each group and determine if it is significant as a candidate gene to have relation to disease.

We will also graph the data to show the differences.

The dataset gave p-values and adjusted pvalue(FDR) itself, but I do not know how they were calculated, thus it is better to do my own analysis.

Null Hypothesis: There is no difference among the sample means of the levels of gene expression, in the genes of interest, within control samples versus CKD patient samples.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a difference among the sample means of the levels of gene expression, in the genes of interest, within control samples versu CKD patient samples.

Part 4: Exploratory Data Analysis for Risk Factor Data¶

1. Chi-Squared Test

We want to determine if there is a significant association between specific gravity (sg) levels and whether or not the person has chronic kidney disease. To determine this, we conduct a Chi-Squared Test to compare the 'sg' and 'classification' variables. The 'sg' variable is nominal, so the values are one of 5 possible values (1.005,1.010,1.015,1.020,1.025). The 'classification' variable tells whether the entry is a ckd patient (1) or not (0). We will use a signifiance level of 0.01 for this test.

Null Hypothesis: The level of specific gravity does not effect the likelihood of having chronic kidney disease.

Alternative Hypothesis: The level of specific gravity does have an effect on the likelihood of having chronic kidney disease.

In [ ]:

The plot above shows the relationship between the sg level and the ckd classification. It shows that the lower sg levels had more cases classified as ckd.

After running the Chi-Squared Test, we get a p-value of 2.507e-37. Based on the obtained p-value, we reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is less than the significance level: 2.507e-37 < 0.01. Therefore, we can conclude that the sg level does indeed have an effect on whether or not someone has chronic kidney disease.

2. ANOVA Test

Now that we know that lower levels of specific gravity (sg) correspond to more cases of chronic kidney disease (ckd), we want to determine if the average number of cases of ckd differ among the different groups of the lower sg levels, namely 1.005, 1.01, 1.015, and 1.017. To determine this, we conduct an ANOVA Test. The 'sg' variable is nominal, so the values are one of 5 possible values (1.005,1.010,1.015,1.020,1.025). The 'classification' variable tells whether the entry is a ckd patient (1) or not (0). We will use a signifiance level of 0.01 for this test.

Null Hypothesis: The mean number of cases of chronic kidney disease are about the same among the different groups of sg levels.

Alternative Hypothesis: The mean number of cases of chronic kidney disease are different among at least 2 different groups of sg levels.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# anova test
groups = [rf_df[rf_df['spec_grav'] == sg_level]['ckd_class'] for sg_level in rf_df['spec_grav'].unique()]
f_statistic, p_value = f_oneway(*groups)
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

# plotting proportion of ckd cases within each sg level category
csg = rf_df.groupby('spec_grav')['ckd_class'].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
csg.plot(kind='bar', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Proportion of CKD cases by specfic gravity level')
plt.xlabel('specific gravity level')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of CKD Cases')
plt.show()

P-value: 4.19183799931205e-60

The plot above shows the proportion of ckd cases by sg level. It shows that with low levels of sg (1.005, 1.01, and 1.015), 100% of the patients have ckd.

The p-value produced by the ANOVA test is 4.1918e-60. This is very small and less than the significance level of 0.01. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the mean number of ckd cases based on sg level is indeed different. This implies that lower levels of sg result in ckd.

A Post Hoc Test can be helpful to identify which specific groups are different from each other and how they are different. For example, if people with a sg level of 1.005 are more likely to have ckd compared to people with a sg level of 1.01 and so on. However, we will not conduct a post hoc test for this project because we are only interested in the general features that have most impact when predicting ckd, rather than the specific differences within a single feature.

We can conclude from this exploratory analysis that ckd can be predicted from low levels of sg, specifically, sg levels of 1.005, 1.01, 1.015, and 1.0174.

Part 5: Machine Learning for Risk Factor Data¶

Here we are using a machine learning method called Support Vector Machines (SVM) due to the high dimensionality of the risk factor dataset. We will create a ML model to predict whether or not one has ckd based on the 7 independent variables identified in our preliminary analysis (specific gravity, hemoglobin, packed cell volume, red blood cell count, albumin, hypertension, and diabetes).

Before we can use the SVM method, we need to normalize the data to deal with high variation and noise which could negatively effect the accuracy of the model. Here, we use z-score normalization due to the wide range of values that the numerical variables have.

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

X = rf_df[['spec_grav', 'hemoglobin', 'packed_cell_vol', 'red_b_cells', 'albumin', 'hypertension', 'diabetes']].values
Y = rf_df[['ckd_class']].values

# Split the data into training and testing sets.
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=20220621)

# Scale the input variable because SVM is dependent on differences in scale for distances
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Define and fit the risk factor SVM model
rfSVMlinear = svm.SVC(kernel='linear', C=0.01)
rfSVMlinear.fit(X_train_scaled, Y_train)

# Predict for the test set
Y_pred = rfSVMlinear.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Display the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False)
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.ylabel('True')
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate decision function scores for the test set
decision_scores = rfSVMlinear.decision_function(X_test_scaled)

# Convert decision scores to probabilities using a sigmoid function
Y_pred_proba = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-decision_scores))

# Calculate and plot residuals
residuals = np.abs(Y_pred_proba - Y_test.flatten())

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

In the above residual plot, the residuals are shown to be scattered and have no particular pattern. This demonstrates the fact that the SVM model's predictions are random, and therefore are not systematically biased toward overestimating or underestimating the true probabilities. This further suggests that this model is performing reasonably well.
